 such as Sìleas na Ceapaich, Mary Queen of Scots, Anne Grant, Janet Hamilton, Isabella Bird, F. Marion McNeill and Denise Mina. There are chapters on women in Gaelic culture, women's relationship to oral traditions and to key literary periods, women's engagements with nationalism, with space, with genre fiction and with the activity of reading.Key features Includes innovative scholarship from leading critics of gender and Scottish Studies, including Sarah Dunnigan (Edinburgh), Carol Anderson (Open University), Pam Perkins (Manitoba), Florence Boos (Iowa)Responds to current developments in the field of feminist and literary studiesIncludes an authoritative introduction and a guide to further reading  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aEnglish literaturexScottish authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aScottish literaturexWomen authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aScottish literaturexWomen authors. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh1 aAnderson, Carol, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBell, Eleanor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoos, Florence S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Rhona, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aByrne, Michel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChristianson, Aileen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDunnigan, Sarah M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrater, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGermanà, Monica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGilbert, Suzanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/